title: For Sale/Trade:  *Pending* Smith & Wesson 637 Airweight J-Frame Revolver
postcontent:
I saw this earlier this year during a sale at the range/gun shop I belong to.  I couldn't pass up the price, so I brought it home with me. The clear coat on the aluminum frame is peeling, I had thought about having it refinished with a color Cerakote job, but I thought I'd see if anyone wanted it as-is first.  Apparently this isn't unheard of with the Airweight frames. In reality, I really don't have the time or the desire to strip the gun down to the frame and put it back together after having a coating applied. The gun was likely made in January of 2015, as that's the date on the sample spent cartridge that comes with a new gun.  I shot it a few times and I thought the trigger was pretty smooth and crisp for a newer J-frame. We have another Model 60LS that had to have a $110 trigger job right out of the box to get all of the bumps and burrs smoothed out.  This one isn't too bad.  If you don't know the model, these are a 5-shot .38 Special revolver. They've been in production since 1950, typically as a backup gun for LEO's.  They are rated to handle +P ammunition, but the .357 Magnum cartridge must not be used in the 637 Airweight. The frame is aluminum; the cylinder, barrel, and internals are steel. This is the Single/Double Action variant with an exposed hammer.  These revolvers are the right size to fit in a coat pocket or purse if you so choose. They also conceal nicely under clothing without the caveats of carrying a semiautomatic.  I'm not really looking for firearm trades, but if you have something interesting we could talk about it.  I'm in the market for a quality long-range rifle scope (Vortex strongly preferred); if you happen to have one to offer I can add cash to make a deal. Buyers must present an Ohio ID and be 21 or over to purchase a handgun.
If you're going to send me a scam offer, at least have a native English speaker proofread your work. You guys make it too easy.
